In order to verify the selectivity of the two methods for Cur, the fluorescence response of the Eu3+-TTA-CTAB-Gd3+ to Cur and possible coexistence metal ions or amino acids was investigated (Fig. 6
                        ). CaCl2, ZnSO4, KCl, AlCl3, NaCl, CuSO4, Mg(NO3)2, BaCl2, Na2CO3 (1.0 × 10−5 mol/L), glycine (Gly), aspartic acid (Asp), cysteine (Cys), alanine (Ala), glucose (Glc), uric acid (UA), lysine acid (Lys), glutamic acid (Glu), tyrosine (Tyr) (5.0 × 10−6 mol/L), BSA (5.0 × 10−7 g/mL), fsDNA (1.0 × 10−7 g/mL), ascorbic acid (AA) (1.0 × 10−6 mol/L) and folic acid (FA) (1.0 × 10−7 mol/L) have little effect on the fluorescence of the Eu3+-TTA-CTAB-Gd3+ system compared with Cur (6.0 × 10−8 mol/L). Compared with the Stokes fluorescence and the NIRL excitation fluorescence method, the former method has good selectivity to ZnSO4, KCl, AlCl3, NaCl, Mg(NO3)2, BaCl2 and Tyr. While the latter method shows good selectivity to CaCl2, CuSO4, Na2CO3, UA, Lys, Glu, BSA, FA, AA and fsDNA. The interference of some metal ions and amino acids on the detection of Cur was also investigated (Table 1
                        ). The possible coexisting substances have little interference to Eu3+-Cur-TTA-CTAB-Gd3+ system within ±5% change range of fluorescence intensity of the two methods except Fe2+ and Cu2+. The NIRL excitation fluorescence method has better anti-interference ability to Zn2+, Glc, AA and Cys.
